  "question": "Why can scam tokens and weird claimable balances reach my Stellar wallet at all?",
  "surface": [
    "stellarDocs.search_protocol_concepts_docs"
  ],
  "golden": {
    "answer": "Stellar is an open network, so someone can create an asset or a claimable balance without first getting your approval. Receiving a reference to an asset is not the same as safely holding, trusting, or endorsing it: non-XLM assets generally need a trustline before they can be held, and a claimable balance still has its own claim conditions. Judge an asset by its issuer and independent official information, not its code, logo, or a message sent with it.",
    "keyFacts": [
      "Explains the open-network premise without calling every unsolicited asset fraudulent.",
      "States the trustline distinction for non-XLM assets."
    ],
    "avoid": [
      "Do NOT say unsolicited entries let the sender spend the recipient's funds.",
      "Do NOT assert every unsolicited asset is fraudulent."
    ],
    "notes": "Avoid claims are deliberately narrow."
  },
